    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u explain what actually happens in my muscles when i do hiit? specifically like how does lactic acid actually get produced and how does my body get rid of it after the workout?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you're doing HIIT, your muscles are working so hard, it's like a frantic little rush of energy, and you start to produce lactic acid, which is a byproduct of anaerobic respiration. Think of it like a sudden, overwhelming surge of energy that the muscles can't keep up with, which is what makes you feel that burning sensation. Your body, in a very clever way, doesn't just dump this lactic acid; it's actually converted into lactate, which is then shuttled around your system. It's a metabolic process that's more complex than just \"lactic acid buildup,\" and it's a key part of how your body adapts to those intense bursts, which is what makes your muscles stronger.",
      "source": "target",
